{{Infobox power station | name = Embalse Nuclear Power Station | name_official = Central Nuclear Embalse | image = Central Nuclear Embalse aerea.JPG | image_caption = | location_map = Argentina | country = [[Argentina]] | coordinates = {{coord|32.232|S|64.443|W|region:AR_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}} | operator = [[Nucleoeléctrica Argentina Sociedad Anónima]] | status = R | construction_began = 1974 | commissioned = January 20, 1984 | decommissioned = | ps_units_operational = <del>{{nowrap|648 MW}}</del> | ps_units_uc = {{nowrap|683 MW}} | np_reactor_type = [[PHWR]] | np_reactor_supplier = [[CANDU]] | ps_thermal_capacity = 2,015 [[MWt]] | ps_heating_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = 5,192 GW·h (2009) | website = {{URL|http://www.candu.org/nasa.html}} | ps_units_planned = }}
The '''Embalse Nuclear Power Station''' ({{lang-es|Central Nuclear Embalse}}) is one of three operational [[nuclear power plant]]s in [[Argentina]]. It is located on the southern shore of a [[Reservoir (water)|reservoir]] on the Río Tercero, near the city of [[Embalse, Córdoba|Embalse]], [[Córdoba Province (Argentina)|Córdoba]], 110&nbsp;km south-southwest of [[Córdoba, Argentina|Córdoba City]].
The plant is a [[CANDU reactor|CANDU]] [[Pressurised Heavy Water Reactor]] (PHWR). It employs [[natural uranium]] (that is, with 0.72% of <sup>235</sup>U) and uses [[heavy water]] for cooling and neutron moderation. It has a thermal power of 2,109&nbsp;[[Watt#Electrical and thermal watts|MW<sub>th</sub>]], and generates 648&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW<sub>e</sub>]] of electricity, with a net output of about 600&nbsp;MW<sub>e</sub>, supplying nearly 4.5% of the production of the [[Argentine Interconnection System]] (2005).
Additionally, Embalse produces the [[cobalt-60]] radioisotope, which is employed in medicine (cancer therapy) and industrial applications. Argentina is one of the largest producers and exporters of this isotope in the world,<ref name=ref1>http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/non-power-nuclear-applications/radioisotopes-research/radioisotopes-in-medicine.aspx</ref> along with [[Canada]] and [[Russia]].
Embalse was started in 1974 and began operation in 1983 (first criticality 13 March 1983, declared commercial 20 January 1984). It was built by an [[Italy|Italian]]-Canadian consortium formed by [[Atomic Energy of Canada Limited|AECL]], acting as the [[Turnkey|"turn-key"]] supplier of the nuclear portion, and [[:it:Italimpianti|Italimpianti]], the "turn-key" supplier of the conventional portion.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://canteach.candu.org/Content%20Library/19930101.pdf | title =A Short History of the CANDU Nuclear Power System | last1 = Brooks | first1 = Gord L. | date = 2 December 2002 | website = canteach.candu.org | publisher = | access-date = 4 September 2016 | quote = p.18, In the case of the Cordoba (Argentina) project, AECL originally contracted to act as the "turn-key" supplier of the nuclear portion of the plant with its Italian partner, Italimpianti, acting as the "turn-key" supplier of the conventional portion.}}</ref>
On 31 December 2015, the plant was taken offline, having completed its first operating cycle of about 30 years.
On 1 September 2016, the plant received the last two of four [[Steam generator (nuclear power)|steam generators]], fundamental elements for the life extension of the plant. The plant is being reconditioned to deliver power for another 30 years: the replacement of the four steam generators is one of the key steps. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.na-sa.com.ar/es/novedades/llegaron-los-dos-ultimos-generadores-de-vapor-para-la-central-nuclear-embalse |title=Llegaron los dos últimos generadores de vapor para la Central Nuclear Embalse |last1= |first1= |date=1 September 2016 |website=canteach.candu.org |publisher=Nucleoeléctrica Argentina S.A. |language=ES |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903233336/http://www.na-sa.com.ar/es/novedades/llegaron-los-dos-ultimos-generadores-de-vapor-para-la-central-nuclear-embalse |archive-date=2016-09-03 |dead-url=no |access-date=4 September 2016 |quote= |df= }}</ref> The plant is expected to be offline until 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snclavalin.com/en/embalse-nuclear-generating-station-life-extension |title=Embalse Nuclear Generating Station Life Extension |last1= |first1= |date=13 April 2016 |website=www.snclavalin.com |language= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304114813/http://www.snclavalin.com/en/embalse-nuclear-generating-station-life-extension |archive-date=4 March 2017 |dead-url=no |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref> and will have a power uprate to a gross capacity of 683 MW.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nucnet.org/all-the-news/2016/01/06/argentina-s-embalse-shuts-down-for-major-refurbishment-programme/print |title=Argentina’s Embalse Shuts Down For Major Refurbishment Programme |last1= |first1= |date=6 January 2016 |website=www.nucnet.org |language= |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>
