{{Infobox company | name = Enefit Kaevandused AS | logo = | caption = | type = subsidiary of [[Eesti Energia]] | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = 1945 | founder = | defunct = | location_city = [[Jõhvi]] | location_country = [[Estonia]] | locations = | area_served = North–east Estonia | key_people = Valeri Abramov ([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]]) | industry = Mining | products = [[Oil shale]] | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = 3,150 (2009) | parent = [[Eesti Energia]] | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''Enefit Kaevandused''' (former names: '''Eesti Põlevkivi''' and '''Eesti Energia Kaevandused''') is a mining company located in [[Jõhvi]], [[Estonia]]. It is a subsidiary of [[Eesti Energia]], an Estonian state-owned energy company. The core activity of Enefit Kaevandused is [[Oil shale|oil-shale]] [[mining]]. The produced oil shale is mainly used to fuel [[Narva Power Plants|oil shale-fired power stations in the north–east of Estonia]].<ref name=bc050210> {{cite news | publisher= The Baltic Course | url= http://www.baltic-course.com/rus/konferencii/?doc=23352 | title = Estonian oil shale mining industry posted record of a decade due to cold weather in January | author = Juhan Tere | date = 2010-02-05 | accessdate=2010-04-03}} </ref> The company has 3,150&nbsp;employees.<ref name=bc061009> {{cite news | publisher= The Baltic Course | url= http://www.baltic-course.com/rus/konferencii/?doc=19036 | title = Eesti Energia Kaevandused makes 49 employees redundant | author = Juhan Tere | date = 2009-10-06 | accessdate=2010-04-03}} </ref> The [[chief executive officer]] is Valeri Abramov.<ref name=err130218> {{cite news | url= https://www.err.ee/682814/ahti-puuri-asemel-saab-enefit-kaevanduste-juhiks-valeri-abramov | title= Ahti Puuri asemel saab Enefit Kaevanduste juhiks Valeri Abramov | trans-title = Valeri Abramov becomes the head of Enefit Kaevandused instead of Ahti Puur | publisher = [[Eesti Rahvusringhääling|ERR]] | date = 2018-02-13 | accessdate=2018-08-25}} </ref>
==History== Enefit Kaevandused were established in June 1945 as Eesti Põlevkivi, also known by its name in Russian ''Estonslanets''. It was created by merging Kukruse and Käva II mines. In 1946, it took over Viivikonna mine.<ref name=pihlamagi> {{Cite journal | last1 = Pihlamägi | first1 = Maie | title= Policy of transition: Industry in the Estonian SSR during the first post-war five-year plan (1946–1950) | url= http://www.kirj.ee/public/Acta_hist/2010/acta-2010-15-146-166.pdf | journal= Acta Historica Tallinnensia | publisher=Estonian Academy Publishers | volume=15 | pages=146–166 | year= 2010 | accessdate=2014-08-21 | doi= 10.3176/hist.2010.1.07 | format = PDF}} </ref>
In 1999, Government of Estonia handed 51% of shares of Eesti Põlevkivi to Narva Elektrijaamad.<ref name=eta020699> {{Cite news | title = Estonian government allocates energy shares ahead of privatization | agency = ETA | date = 1999-06-02 | url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=BBAB&d_place=BBAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F99F83B023DAE01&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | accessdate =2013-01-19 | id = {{subscription required}}}} </ref> In 2003, Government transferred remained 49% stake in Eesti Põlevkivi to Eesti Energia. Also Narva Elektrijaamad-owned 51% stake was transferred to Eesti Energia and Eesti Põlevkivi became a fully owned subsidiary of Eesti Energia.<ref name=eiu170103> {{Cite news | title = Estonia industry: Government to give Eesti Energia stake in Eesti Polevkivi | work = [[Economist Intelligence Unit]] | date = 2003-01-17 | url= http://business.highbeam.com/437192/article-1G1-96632647/estonia-industry-government-give-eesti-energia-stake | accessdate =2013-01-19 | id = {{subscription required}}}} </ref>
==Operations== Enefit Kaevandused has following subsidiaries: * Estonia Underground Mine - oil-shale mining * Narva Open-Cast - oil-shale mining * AS Põlevkivi Raudtee - rail transportation * [[Orica]] Eesti OÜ (35% of shares) - production of explosives
