'''Michael Mobbs''' is a Sydney-based author and environmental consultant. He graduated from the [[Australian National University]] with a Bachelor of Laws in 1975<ref name="Alderman">{{cite web|title=Michael Mobbs|url=http://www.sydneyaldermen.com.au/alderman/michael-mobbs/|website=City of Sydney|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> and then worked as an environmental lawyer for 19 years. Through this work he developed an interest in [[sustainability]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocitizenaustralia.com.au/michael-mobbs-sustainable-house-sydney/ |title=Michael Mobbs Australia Eco Citizen |accessdate=1 May 2013 }}</ref> Mobbs served as an Independent Alderman on the [[Sydney City Council|City of Sydney Council]] from 1985–1987.<ref name="Alderman" /> In the 1990s Mobbs converted his [[Chippendale, New South Wales|Chippendale]] home into a more sustainable house by modifying the water, energy and waste systems. He regularly opens his house for guided public tours.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/gardening/stories/s811232.htm |title=Gardening Australia – Fact Sheet: Michael Mobbs |accessdate=1 May 2013 }}</ref>

In 2009, ''The (Sydney) Magazine'' listed Michael Mobbs as one of Sydney's 100 most influential people.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefifthestate.com.au/archives/8208/ |title=Sydney's top 100 |accessdate=1 May 2013 }}</ref> He has an ongoing role in the urban food growing movement in Sydney and has been a contributor to the Chippendale verge gardens.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sustainablechippendale.com/road-gardens/2011/7/11/chippendale-street-gardens.html |title=Sustainable Chippendale Gardening |accessdate=1 May 2013 }}</ref>

